{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"406041fb-eba3-4992-a5b3-dbc26392d9f3","content":"Here's your specific plan based on what's already on this machine (.NET 10.0.201, JDK 17 ✓):\n\n---\n\n## Step-by-step: MAUI Android build on headless Linux CI\n\n### 1. Install the MAUI workload (includes Android SDK)\n\n```bash\nsudo dotnet workload install maui-android\n```\n\nThis pulls in the `android` workload + Android SDK, build tools, and platform packages automatically. No need to install Android Studio or `sdkmanager` separately — the .NET workload handles it.\n\n### 2. Find the exact versions it installed\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list                    # confirms maui-android is installed\nls ~/.android/sdk/                      # default Android SDK location on Linux\nls ~/.android/sdk/platforms/            # shows which API level (e.g. android-35)\nls ~/.android/sdk/build-tools/          # shows build-tools version\n```\n\nIf your project targets a specific API level not included, you can add it:\n```bash\n~/.android/sdk/cmdline-tools/latest/bin/sdkmanager \"platforms;android-35\"\n```\n\n### 3. Accept Android SDK licenses (required, non-interactive)\n\n```bash\nyes | ~/.android/sdk/cmdline-tools/latest/bin/sdkmanager --licenses\n```\n\n### 4. Set environment variables\n\n```bash\nexport ANDROID_HOME=\"$HOME/.android/sdk\"\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"/usr/lib/jvm/temurin-17-jdk-amd64\"   # already set here\n```\n\n### 5. Build\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -f net10.0-android   # adjust TFM to match your project (net9.0-android, etc.)\n```\n\nFor a signed release APK:\n```bash\ndotnet publish -f net10.0-android -c Release\n```\n\n### How to find correct versions for a specific project\n\n| Question | How to find it |\n|---|---|\n| Which MAUI workload? | Check your `.csproj` for `<TargetFramework>` — `net9.0-android` → use SDK 9.x workloads; `net10.0-android` → use SDK 10.x |\n| Which Android API level? | Check `<TargetFramework>net10.0-android35.0</TargetFramework>` or `<SupportedOSPlatformVersion>` in your `.csproj` |\n| Which JDK? | .NET MAUI requires JDK 17. You already have it. |\n| Which build-tools? | Managed automatically by the workload. Override with `<AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion>` in `.csproj` if needed. |\n\n### Common CI gotchas\n\n- **First build is slow** — NuGet restore + AOT compilation. Cache `~/.nuget/packages` and `~/.android/sdk` between runs.\n- **Missing fonts/runtime packs** — if you see errors about missing runtime packs, run `dotnet workload restore` in the project directory.\n- **`ANDROID_HOME` not found** — the .NET SDK looks in `~/.android/sdk` by default on Linux but some tasks still require the env var.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf3fad42-a14d-4099-b4ac-fd78f6df1f89","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Good, I have a clear picture now. They have:\n- .NET SDK 10.0.201 (latest), plus 9.0.x SDKs\n- No workloads installed\n- JDK 17 installed (good - Android needs JDK 11 or 17)\n\nNow let me provide a specific, actionable plan for building a MAUI Android app on headless Linux CI.","outputTokens":882},"id":"c66f5605-af34-40d5-be6c-97e84d7be43e","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:50:28.988Z","parentId":"d43308a7-d7e1-4028-8148-0152bcf39ad5"}
